Unsupervised Learning: Trade & Ahead¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

The stock market has consistently proven to be a good place to invest in and save for the future. There are a lot of compelling reasons to invest in stocks. It can help in fighting inflation, create wealth, and also provides some tax benefits. Good steady returns on investments over a long period of time can also grow a lot more than seems possible. Also, thanks to the power of compound interest, the earlier one starts investing, the larger the corpus one can have for retirement. Overall, investing in stocks can help meet life's financial aspirations.

It is important to maintain a diversified portfolio when investing in stocks in order to maximise earnings under any market condition. Having a diversified portfolio tends to yield higher returns and face lower risk by tempering potential losses when the market is down. It is often easy to get lost in a sea of financial metrics to analyze while determining the worth of a stock, and doing the same for a multitude of stocks to identify the right picks for an individual can be a tedious task. By doing a cluster analysis, one can identify stocks that exhibit similar characteristics and ones which exhibit minimum correlation. This will help investors better analyze stocks across different market segments and help protect against risks that could make the portfolio vulnerable to losses.

Objective¶

Trade&Ahead is a financial consultancy firm who provide their customers with personalized investment strategies. They have hired you as a Data Scientist and provided you with data comprising stock price and some financial indicators for a few companies listed under the New York Stock Exchange. They have assigned you the tasks of analyzing the data, grouping the stocks based on the attributes provided, and sharing insights about the characteristics of each group.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Ticker Symbol: An abbreviation used to uniquely identify publicly traded shares of a particular stock on a particular stock market
  • Company: Name of the company
  • GICS Sector: The specific economic sector assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • GICS Sub Industry: The specific sub-industry group assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • Current Price: Current stock price in dollars
  • Price Change: Percentage change in the stock price in 13 weeks
  • Volatility: Standard deviation of the stock price over the past 13 weeks
  • ROE: A measure of financial performance calculated by dividing net income by shareholders' equity (shareholders' equity is equal to a company's assets minus its debt)
  • Cash Ratio: The ratio of a company's total reserves of cash and cash equivalents to its total current liabilities
  • Net Cash Flow: The difference between a company's cash inflows and outflows (in dollars)
  • Net Income: Revenues minus expenses, interest, and taxes (in dollars)
  • Earnings Per Share: Company's net profit divided by the number of common shares it has outstanding (in dollars)
  • Estimated Shares Outstanding: Company's stock currently held by all its shareholders
  • P/E Ratio: Ratio of the company's current stock price to the earnings per share
  • P/B Ratio: Ratio of the company's stock price per share by its book value per share (book value of a company is the net difference between that company's total assets and total liabilities)

Problem Definition¶

  • Trade&Ahead is a financial consultancy developing customized investment plans for its clients. As it is very labour-intensive to scan through hundreds of stock metrics, the problem would be to carry out efficient clustering analysis in order to segment similar NYSE-listed stocks by price and financial indicators, enabling Trade&Ahead to gain knowledge about stock segments from customers for optimal diversification of the portfolio and thereby mitigating market risk. The goal is to identify stock clusters with minimal correlation for enhanced investment strategies.

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(df, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=df, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

                100 * p.get_height() / total

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),

        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Question 4

Cash ratio provides a measure of a company's ability to cover its short-term obligations using only cash and cash equivalents. How does the average cash ratio vary across economic sectors?

In [31]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
sns.barplot(data=df, x='GICS Sector', y='Cash Ratio', ci=False)  ## Choosing 'GICS Sector' for x and 'Cash Ratio' for y
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

Observations

  • The cash ratio analysis provides valuable insights into the liquidity positions and financial management practices of different sectors.

  • Information technology has the highest cash ratio among the sectors. Next in rank are telecommunications services, health care, and financials.

  • High Cash Ratio Sectors: The information technology and telecommunication services continue to have the highest levels of cash ratio, probably on account of their strong cash flow generation, lower capital intensiveness in the case of technology, and strategic investments or merger and acquisition initiatives.

  • The Sectors with Low Cash Ratio are Utilities and Industrials which have a low cash ratio due to the high capital expenditure requirements and dependency on debt financing.

  • Energy has a moderately low cash ratio. Energy firms are usually highly capital-expenditure-intensive and vulnerable to adverse price swings, which may impact their cash positions.

  • The financials depict a moderately high cash ratio. A financial institution has to have a certain level of liquidity for different regulatory requirements imposed by the regulatory authorities, besides the myriad instances of withdrawals by customers.

  • Real Estate-being moderately low-leads in real estate investment with high debt-equity ratios, which the companies mostly engage in. Materials: The cash ratio is low to moderate. Companies in this industry are often cyclical and may require cash to manage price fluctuations and capital expenditures.

Question 5

P/E ratios can help determine the relative value of a company's shares as they signify the amount of money an investor is willing to invest in a single share of a company per dollar of its earnings. How does the P/E ratio vary, on average, across economic sectors?

In [32]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
sns.barplot(data=df, x='GICS Sector', y='P/E Ratio', ci=False)  ## Choosing 'GICS Sector' for x and 'P/E Ratio' for y
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

Observations

  • Energy would have a very high P/E ratio, most probably because of many reasons such as future demand, or supply strain, or renewable energy investments. On the other hand, it might also be an indication of overvaluation, especially when earnings do not catch up with the price.
  • The high P/E ratios for the Information Technology, Health Care, and Real Estate sectors suggest very strong growth expectations and readiness by investors to pay for future earnings at a premium.
  • Although low P/E ratios in sectors such as Utilities and Financials would be considered value-oriented, investors are essentially giving up high growth for current earnings and dividends.
  • The general P/E pattern across industries gives broad market sentiment and expectations on future economic conditions and industry-specific factors.

Question 6:

Volatility accounts for the fluctuation in the stock price. A stock with high volatility will witness sharper price changes, making it a riskier investment. Let's see how volatility varies, on average, across economic sectors.

In [33]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
sns.barplot(data=df, x='GICS Sector', y='Volatility', ci=False)  ## Choosing 'GICS Sector' for x and 'Volatility' for y
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

Observations

  • Cyclical sectors like Energy, Materials, and Consumer Discretionary tend to exhibit higher volatility compared to stable sectors like Consumer Staples and Utilities.
  • Sectors with high growth potential and rapid innovation, such as Information Technology, often experience greater price fluctuations.
  • Sectors that are sensitive to economic conditions, like Financials and Industrials, tend to have moderate to high volatility.
  • Information Technology displays relatively high volatility, typical for the tech sector due to rapid innovation, competitive pressures, and evolving consumer preferences.

clusters = range(1, 15)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction = model.predict(k_means_df)
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(k_means_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / k_means_df.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)

Hierarchical Clustering¶

Computing Cophenetic Correlation¶

In [54]:
hc_df = subset_scaled_df.copy()
In [55]:
# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"] ## Complete the code to add distance metrics

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"] ## Complete the code to add linkages

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(hc_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

# printing the combination of distance metric and linkage method with the highest cophenetic correlation
print('*'*100)
print(
    "Highest cophenetic correlation is {}, which is obtained with {} distance and {} linkage.".format(
        high_cophenet_corr, high_dm_lm[0].capitalize(), high_dm_lm[1]
    )
)

In [57]:
# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]

# lists to save results of cophenetic correlation calculation
compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]
compare = []

# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage methods above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(hc_df, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

    compare.append([method, coph_corr])
In [58]:

K-means vs Hierarchical Clustering¶

We will compare the following:

  1. Clustering technique that took less time for execution
  2. Clustering technique gave more distinct clusters, or same cluster?
  3. Observations that are there in the similar clusters of both algorithms
  4. Clusters that are obtained as the appropriate number of clusters from both algorithms
  5. Differences or similarities you obtained in the cluster profiles from both the clustering techniques.

1. Execution time between K-Means and Hierarchical

In [68]:
import time
# Record the start time for K-means
start_time_kmeans = time.time()

# K-means clustering
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=6, random_state=1)
kmeans.fit(k_means_df)
k_means_df["KM_segments"] = kmeans.labels_

# Record the end time for K-means
end_time_kmeans = time.time()

# Calculate the execution time for K-means
execution_time_kmeans = end_time_kmeans - start_time_kmeans


# Record the start time for Hierarchical clustering
start_time_hc = time.time()

# Hierarchical clustering
HCmodel = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=6, metric='euclidean', linkage='ward')
HCmodel.fit(hc_df)
hc_df["HC_segments"] = HCmodel.labels_

# Record the end time for Hierarchical clustering
end_time_hc = time.time()

# Calculate the execution time for Hierarchical clustering
execution_time_hc = end_time_hc - start_time_hc

# Print the execution times
print(f"K-means execution time: {execution_time_kmeans} seconds")
print(f"Hierarchical clustering execution time: {execution_time_hc} seconds")

# Compare execution times
if execution_time_kmeans < execution_time_hc:
    print("K-means took less time for execution.")
else:
    print("Hierarchical clustering took less time for execution.")

Observations

Key Similarities:

  • Both approaches detect six clusters with very similar segment distributions.
  • Cluster 5 in both methods represents the same, having the highest current price of around 327 USD and the highest P/E Ratio of ~400.
  • Segment 3 in K-means and Segment 3 in Hierarchical Clustering have similar profiles in Current Price of around 72 USD, Volatility (~1.4), ROE at 25-26%, and Net Income of $1.5B.
  • In K-means Segment 2 & HC Segment 1, those negative cash flow segments for instance, include an extremely high stock ROE > 600% in rate, and with the net income as negative.

Key Differences: Cluster Composition:

  • Hierarchical clustering seems to produce more balanced cluster sizes, while in k-means clusters, one dominant group clearly outbalances the other: Segment 3 has 285 stocks in Hierarchical clustering.

  • k-means segment 2 also represented the highest ROE of 802%, divided across HC segments 1 and 2.

Cash Ratios and Liquidity:

  • HC Segmentation: Segment 2 is worth ~360 Cash Ratio against the K-means, Segment 4 of ~279. HC segments reflect clearer liquidity differences across groups.

P/E and P/B Variability:

  • Hierarchical clustering segments have a greater spread in the P/B Ratios. For example, Segment 2 has 25.26, while its closest K-means counterpart, Segment 4, has 15.09. HC Segment 4 Low-priced Stocks will have a very high P/E Ratio, standing at 85.56 as opposed to 75.63 by K-means

While k-means makes an explicit separation when it comes to extreme values, Hierarchical Clustering has even distribution. While the trends of liquidity and valuation are so subtle, Hierarchical Clustering may serve better; in K-means, the volatility and outliers are accentuated more sharply. While Hierarchical Clustering can be used to extract more interpretable groupings for the investment strategy, the K-means will be more useful for quick segmentation and finding the pattern.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • HC seems to have the largest diversified portfolio, consisting of companies in Industrials, Financials, Health Care, and Consumer Discretionary within HC Cluster 3. Stocks within this cluster would be consistent with a diversified large-cap portfolio or index fund strategy that reduces risk through broad market exposure.
  • K-means has been more sensitive to outliers than Hierarchical. This can lead to distortions.
  • The dataset is quite small. This seems to work well with Hierarchical clustering where computational complexity is not a concern.
  • The generation of a dendrogram under Hierarchical clustering allows for flexible cluster selection.
  • Investment in stocks in cluster 3 under Hierarchical clustering is safer based on the diverse nature and the values across the various features.
  • Stocks in cluster 4 under Hierarchical clustering have the lowest price, coupled with a negative price change and high volatility. It is risky to invest in stocks in cluster 4.
  • K-means Cluster 1 displays less volatility and price fluctuations compared to other clusters, indicating a conservative investment approach. This could be suitable for risk-averse investors seeking stability and moderate returns.
  • External economic and geopolitical events can significantly impact the stock market. We need to stay informed about these events and adjust portfolio strategies as needed to mitigate potential risks.
  • The cluster analysis is only a starting point for identifying potential investment opportunities or risks. It will be useful for investors to perform additional due diligence, including in-depth company analysis and financial statement review, before making any investment decisions. Consulting with a qualified financial advisor will be great in this regard.
